{"type":"message","id":"5fcbd240","parentId":"a54d25c3","timestamp":"2026-04-14T10:40:49.650Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have the context. Let me look at the current sessions to compare against the last known state. \n\nThe last heartbeat state from memory says:\n- at 09:53 UTC:\n  - cron:e7885813 (Agent Status), cron:ed2d0b5d, cron:6f3323ef running\n  - QLHV group (-5163901258): marked done/cleared\n  - DTLX group (-5168104492): active per Lead request for API test\n  - Pipeline: HEALTHY\n  - No blockers\n\nCurrent time: 10:39 UTC\n\nLooking at current sessions:\n\n\n- cron:ed2d0b5d (5p progress) is still running ✅\n- cron:6f3323ef (5p DTLX) is still running ✅\n- cron:e7885813 (Agent Status) is still showing as running but appears to have been aborted, though the session record hasn't been updated to reflect that yet\n- QLHV group (-5163901258) is still marked running but wrapped up over 25 minutes ago\n- DTLX group (-5168104492) is also showing as running but actually completed 58 minutes ago\n\nLooking at the 5p update report from 10:31 UTC, it mentioned the Agent Status cron was still running and unusually long, but that report is now 8 minutes old.\n\nThe cron:e7885813 session is marked as running with a timestamp from 10:03 UTC, and the last message was an \"aborted\" error - so it's likely stalled. But checking the updatedAt times, both cron:ed2d0b5d and cron:6f3323ef have fresher timestamps (10:34 and 10:36 UTC respectively), suggesting they restarted more recently than the initial report indicated. There's also a cron:ac986a8d that's been running since 10:04 UTC. Looking at the session timestamps more carefully, the cron:e7885813 appears to be stale—it was aborted around 10:04 UTC based on the message timestamp, but the session's updatedAt hasn't refreshed, suggesting it should be cleaned up from the active list. Looking at the cron:e7885813 session, it started running at 10:03:26 UTC and shows as still running with updatedAt at 10:36:47, but the actual message history reveals it was aborted at 10:04:40 UTC—that's a significant discrepancy where the session status hasn't caught up with the real state. The most recent 5p report from 10:31 UTC already flagged this as an unusually long-running session, so it's been stuck for at least 35 minutes. and noted it's unusually long. This was flagged then. Now at 10:39, it's still running in the sessions list but was actually aborted at 10:04. The status hasn't been refreshed since.\n\n2. **cron:ac986a8d** — started at 10:04:31, still running. This is a \"Send this exact message to Telegram group -5163901258\" cron. It seems to be trying to send a message but has been running for 35 minutes. This might be a new concern.\n\nActually, I need to be careful here. Let me compare more carefully what was known at the last heartbeat report vs now.\n\nThe last report I can find is from 10:31 UTC in the QLHV group session. It noted:\n- cron:e7885813 (Agent Status to Lead) — STILL RUNNING ⚠️ — active since 10:00 UTC, now ~29 min\n- The cron sessions ed2d0b5d and 6f3323ef are both still running as expected.\n\nNow looking at the current snapshot at 10:39 UTC, the main change is cron:ac986a8d which is attempting to send a message to the Telegram group but appears stuck in a loop trying to locate the session. The e7885813 session is still showing as running in the status even though it was actually aborted at 10:04, which suggests the session metadata hasn't caught up with reality.\n\nThere's also an older cron session (53c5832a from the previous day) that appears to still be listed but is no longer relevant to the current state. These stale session listings are likely due to the heartbeat-state.json being empty or disabled, so I'm working from historical memory rather than the actual current state.\n\nLooking at the running sessions I can confirm: the 5p crons ed2d0b5d and 6f3323ef are still active as expected, and ac986a8d is attempting to